class Access  modifier =>

If you donâ€™t write any access specifier for class Animal, the default is internal.

That means:

Animal is accessible only inside the same assembly/project.

If you want it accessible from another assembly (e.g., another DLL), you must explicitly mark it public.

Example:

public class Animal { }   // Accessible everywhere
internal class Animal { } // Default if nothing is written

In C#
Top-level classes (like your class Animal)

You can declare them as:

public â†’ accessible everywhere.

internal â†’ accessible only within the same assembly/project.

âŒ You cannot make a top-level class private or protected.

âœ… Reason: If a class is private or protected at the top level, nobody outside could ever reference it, so it makes no sense.

Nested classes (a class inside another class)

You can use all access modifiers:

public

private

protected

internal

protected internal

private protected

Example:

class Outer
{
    private class InnerPrivate { }     // only accessible inside Outer
    protected class InnerProtected { } // accessible in derived classes
    public class InnerPublic { }       // accessible everywhere
}


#####################################################################################################

Method Access Modifier =>

For methods (like Speak()):

If you donâ€™t write anything, the default is private.

But here, you wrote public, so itâ€™s explicitly public.

Example:

class Animal
{
    void Eat()  // Default = private (accessible only inside Animal class)
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Animal eats");
    }

    public void Speak()  // Explicitly public
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Animal can speak");
    }
}

ðŸ”¹ Quick Summary

Namespace â†’ no access specifier allowed (always global scope, depends on classes).

Class (default) â†’ internal (visible inside same assembly).

Method (default) â†’ private (visible only inside its class).
